## (1)(a) WiFi Security Protocols

> Describe the security protocols used in the IEEE802.11 family (from a to ax). *(8 marks)*

> *Learn more: [Standards Organizations](/wireless-communications/standards-organizations)*

WiFi security evolved through four main protocols:

**WEP (802.11, 802.11a/b)**
- Wired Equivalent Privacy
- RC4 encryption with 40-bit or 104-bit keys
- **Broken** - IV (initialization vector) reuse makes it easy to crack

**WPA (interim fix for 802.11g)**
- Wi-Fi Protected Access
- Still RC4, but added TKIP (Temporal Key Integrity Protocol)
- Better key management, but still vulnerable

**WPA2 (802.11i, used in 802.11n/ac)**
- Uses **AES-CCMP** encryption (much stronger)
- Two modes: Personal (PSK) and Enterprise (802.1X)
- Solid security for many years

**WPA3 (802.11ax / Wi-Fi 6)**
- **SAE** (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals) replaces PSK
- **Forward secrecy** - past traffic stays safe even if password cracked later
- Protected Management Frames mandatory
- 192-bit security suite for enterprise

| Standard | Security | Encryption | Status |
|----------|----------|------------|--------|
| 802.11/a/b | WEP | RC4 | Broken |
| 802.11g | WPA | RC4 + TKIP | Weak |
| 802.11i/n/ac | WPA2 | AES-CCMP | Good |
| 802.11ax | WPA3 | AES + SAE | Current |

> **Evolution: WEP → WPA → WPA2 → WPA3**

